sec.p:
Based on and modified from criteria set by Beckung et al21 and Eliasson et al,22 participants were divided into 3 groups according to hand function:


Mild: the paretic hand manipulates without restrictions but with limitations in more advanced fine motor skills;



Moderate: the paretic hand has only holding function during manipulation;



Severe motor impairment: the paretic hand has no functional ability.

We calculated the parameters of an a priori sample of 111 participants to be enrolled, 37 patients for each group, considering a delta value of the primary outcome measure (affected limb function measured with Besta and Quality of Upper Extremity Skills Test [QUEST] scales) set at 30% (1 – β = 0.80; α = 0.05; πi = 0.15).

The analysis of this scale consisted in calculating 5 scores according to the algorithms given in the scale manual (range, 0-100). The scores are Dissociated movements, Grasps, Weight bearing, Protective extension, and Total score. Furthermore, adjunctive scores were calculated for each subject by summing up similar items, and a value of 1 was assigned to the score every time the answer was “yes.” The 4 homogenous groups of items were as follows:



dissociated movements (shoulder, elbow, wrist, fingers): 32 items;



grasp (cube of 2.5 cm, cereal, pencil or pen): 12 items;



weight bearing (prone, quadruped): 25 items;



protective extension (front, lateral, back): 18 items.

The scores were calculated separately for the left and right hand (in order to separate the evaluation of the affected and the unaffected hand) for each subject.
